'''James "Jase" Bolger''' (born February 2, 1971) has served as the [[List of Speakers of the Michigan House of Representatives|71st]] and current Speaker of the [[Michigan House of Representatives]] since January 12, 2011.<ref name=MLive /> Bolger is a member of the [[Michigan Republican Party|Republican Party]], and has represented Michigan's 63rd house district since 2009.<ref name=MLive />

==Personal life, education and career==
James "Jase" Bolger was born in [[Grand Rapids, Michigan]], the son of James and Eileen Bolger.<ref name=MLive>Davis, Paula M. (January 9, 2011). [http://www.mlive.com/news/kalamazoo/index.ssf/2011/01/michigan_house_speaker_jase_bo.html Michigan House Speaker Jase Bolger says GOP has 'no excuses,' must deliver results]. ''Kalamazoo Gazette''.</ref>  Because of his father's job as a [[Michigan State Police]] trooper, the family moved around the state often, before settling in [[Charlotte, Michigan]] when Jase entered first grade.<ref name=MLive /> Jase graduated [[Western Michigan University]] with a Bachelor of Business Administration with a dual major in Finance and Political Science.<ref name=RSLC>[http://www.rslc.com/bio_jase_bolger Speaker Jase Bolger Bio, Featured Leader]. ''Republican State Leadership Committee''.</ref>

Prior to entering politics, Bolger founded (and continues to help operate) a small business that updates phone records for Fortune 100 companies.

Bolger was an Eagle Scout. He has been involved with AYSO Soccer, the Rotary, United Way, the KAAAP mentor program, Oaklawn Hospital, the Knights of Columbus, and several Chambers of Commerce.<ref name=MLive />

Bolger is married to his high school sweetheart, and they have two children. Jase and his family are Roman Catholic and members of St. Mary Parish in Marshall.<ref name=MLive />

==Political career==
Bolger was first elected to public office in 2004 as a Calhoun County Commissioner, he was later reelected for the same post in 2006.<ref name=WMUGOP>Western Michigan University GOP (May 21, 2008). [http://wmugop.blogspot.com/2008/05/jase-bolger-for-state-representative.html Jase Bolger for State Representative]. ''WMUGOP Blogspot.''</ref> One of his stated priorities as a Commissioner was to minimize the county's spending which he believed was necessary to secure the county's future.<ref name=RSLC /> During his time as county commissioner Bolger worked with the Democratic majority to achieve consolidation for three [[911]] [[Calhoun County, Michigan|Calhoun County]] dispatchers.<ref name=BOCminutes>Calhoun County Board of Commissioners (Febaruary 7, 2008)[http://www.calhouncountymi.gov/assets/1/7/080207_BOC_Minutes.pdf Board of Commissioners Meeting Minutes] ''Calhouncountymi.gov''</ref> The consolidation of the Battle Creek, Albion and Marshall centers into a single center, located in Marshall, resulted in improved service and a net saving of $1.5 million for local taxpayers.<ref>VoIP Channel (June 6, 2008).[http://cisconary.com/voip/mpsc-approves-60cent-charge-on-all-911-calls/ MPSC Approves 60cent Charge on all 911 calls]. ''Cisconary.com''</ref>

Bolger was first elected as a State Representative in November 2008, when he defeated Democratic nominee Phyllis Smith by a 13-point margin.<ref name=Election2008 /> He was subsequently reelected in 2010 and 2012 and is in his second term as Speaker.<ref name=Election2010 /><ref name=Election2012 /> In 2012, Democrats campaigned heavily trying to defeat Bolger, spending nearly $1 million on mail, television and radio [[attack ad]]s; however, Bolger won re-election to his third and final term.<ref name=KZoo>Klug, Fritz (November 7, 2012). [http://www.mlive.com/news/kalamazoo/index.ssf/2012/11/house_speaker_jase_bolger_clai.html House Speaker Jase Bolger claims victory in re-election bid against Bill Farmer] ''Kalamazoo Gazette''.</ref> Under Bolger's leadership, Republicans retained their majority in the Michigan House while President [[Barack Obama]] was re-elected by a 9.5 point margin in Michigan, and [[U.S. Senator]] [[Debbie Stabenow]] was re-elected by a 20 point margin.<ref name=election2012FedMI>[http://www.pressandguide.com/articles/2012/11/07/business/doc509a731d467e9483310845.txt ELECTION 2012: NATION: President Obama wins second term; Stabenow, Dingell, Conyers win]. ''Press & Guide''.</ref>

He represents Michigan's 63rd legislative District, which includes the eastern Kalamazoo County city of Galesburg and the townships of Brady, Charleston, Climax, Comstock, Kalamazoo, Pavilion, Richland, Ross and Wakeshma; as well as the central/southern Calhoun County city of Marshall, village of Athens, Burlington, Homer, Tekonsha and the townships of Athens, Burlington, Clarendon, Eckford, Emmett, Fredonia, Homer, Leroy, Marengo, Marshall, Newton and Tekonsha.<ref name=DistrictMap>State of Michigan [http://www.michigan.gov/documents/House_63_30705_7.pdf Map of Michigan's 63rd District]. ''Michigan.gov.''</ref>

==Political positions and initiatives==
Speaker Bolger was elected as House leader in 2011, since then numerous legislative packages that have aided Michigan's recovery have passed. Specifically, the Michigan House has passed legislation to cut duplicative regulation, as well as reforming the tax structure and pension systems.<ref name=CapCon /><ref>http://www.michigan.gov/lara/0,4601,7-154-35738-316912--,00.html</ref> In addition to those initiatives, the Speaker has worked with Republicans statewide to pass right-to-work legislation and education reform measures.<ref name=RTWMPRN /> Under Speaker Bolger's leadership the Michigan House has also passed a balanced budget each of the last three years.<ref name="michigan.gov">State of Michigan (June 13, 2013). [http://michigan.gov/snyder/0,4668,7-277--305808--,00.html Michigan's 2014 budget balanced and on time]. ''Michigan.gov''.</ref>

===Education reform===
During Bolger's term as Speaker he has achieved bipartisan support for education reform.<ref name=HouseRollCall1>House Roll Call, Tenure Reform (June 30, 2011). [http://michiganvotes.org/RollCall.aspx?ID=576861 2011 House Bill 4625: Make it easier to fire ineffective teachers (House Roll Call 294)] ''Roll Call Votes''.</ref><ref name=HouseRollCall2>House Roll Call, Tenure Reform (June 30, 2011). [http://michiganvotes.org/RollCall.aspx?ID=576869 2011 House Bill 4627: Ban laying off more effective but less senior teachers first (<U+201C>LIFO<U+201D>) (House Roll Call 296)] ''Roll Call Votes''.</ref> Since 2011 the Michigan House of Representatives have passed numerous education reforms including tenure reform, expansion of cyber and charter school choices, teacher benefit reforms and early childhood development investment.<ref name=HouseRollCall1 /><ref name=HouseRollCall2 /><ref name=tenurereform /><ref name=schoolchoice /><ref name=MPSERS /><ref name=MPREd />

During Bolger's first year as Speaker, the House passed tenure reform.<ref name=tenurereform>Mack, Julie (July 15, 2011). [http://www.mlive.com/news/kalamazoo/index.ssf/2011/07/michigan_tenure_reform_the_rea.html Michigan tenure reform: The real ways in which it could help and hurt teachers (with video)] ''Kalamazoo Gazette''.</ref> Tenure reform in Michigan guaranteed students would not be left with an underperforming teacher, or lose a teacher who is exceeding.<ref name=tenurereform /> Tenure reform made it easier for a school district to fire ineffective teachers, and also banned the [[LIFO (education)|last in first out]] approach was so often used.<ref name=tenurereform />

In addition to tenure reform, Bolger and the House passed legislation that expanded school choice options, guaranteeing more students access to cyber and charter schools; the legislation passed with bipartisan support.<ref name=schoolchoice>Murray, Dave (May 20, 2012). [http://www.mlive.com/education/index.ssf/2012/05/jase_bolger_theres_no_republic.html Jase Bolger: There's no Republican conspiracy to eliminate public schools, we agree with Obama] ''MLive.com''.</ref> The school choice legislation gradually lifts the cap on charter schools authorized by universities, and allows for more cyber school options.<ref name=tenurereform /><ref name=schoolchoice />

Under the Speaker's leadership teacher benefit reforms were also accomplished.<ref name=MPSERS>Eggert, Dave (June 14, 2012). [http://www.mlive.com/education/index.ssf/2012/06/deal_reached_on_changing_teach.html Tentative deal reached on big changes in Michigan's teacher retirement system] ''MLive.com''.</ref> The legislation, which is described as the biggest change in the state's teacher retirement system in a generation, allows school districts to allocate less towards retirement pensions, and more towards students.<ref name=MPSERS /> School district leaders have noted the change to retirement pension requirements have been a blessing, saying the separation allows school districts to spend more on school operations.<ref name=MPSERS /><ref name=edbud1>Dickson, James and Darren Littell (February 6, 2014). [http://blogs.detroitnews.com/politics/2014/02/06/darren-littell-gov-snyders-education-record-sterling/ Darren Littell: Clearing the air on Gov. Snyder's education spending] ''The Detroit News''.</ref> The reform also created the option for teachers to commit more towards their own retirement, or have the option for a smaller pension.<ref name=MPSERS />

The Republican-led House under Bolger recently increased funding for early childhood development by $65 million in 2013.<ref name=MPREd /><ref name=BridgeEd>Melot, Derek (January 9, 2013). [http://bridgemi.com/2013/01/bolger-backs-bigger-dollars-for-early-childhood/ Bolger backs bigger dollars for early childhood] ''Bridge Magazine''.</ref> The changes to funding for early childhood development have resulted in at least 16,000 more students being able to attend pre-k schooling.<ref name=MPREd>Dwyer, Dustin (May 28, 2013). [http://stateofopportunity.michiganradio.org/post/65-million-increase-early-ed-expected-pass-creates-16000-new-preschool-slots-michigan $65 million increase for early ed expected to pass; creates 16,000 new preschool slots in Michigan] ''Michigan Public Radio''.</ref><ref>Brownfield, Mike (June 19, 2013). [http://www.michigan.gov/snyder/0,4668,7-277-60279-306446--,00.html Investing in Education] ''Michigan.gov''.</ref> In regards to increased early childhood development funding Speaker Bolger said, 
{{Quote|"We should expand early childhood education opportunities as investments to help kids succeed. Those investments also will provide savings to our schools and communities years later as those students learn <U+2014> and a decade later as they find success through working and don<U+2019>t enter our criminal justice system."<ref name=BridgeEd />}}
The Speaker's comments on early childhood funding were applauded by the Children<U+2019>s Leadership Council of Michigan.<ref name=BridgeEd />

===Job growth===
Michigan saw a sharp decline in the labor force starting in 2008 and lasting until 2011, which resulted in 800,000 jobs lost.<ref name=BLSnumbers />  In 2009, Michigan's unemployment rate hit a record-high 14.2 percent.<ref name=BLSnumbers /><ref name=unemploymentdrops>Oosting, Jonathan (March 5, 2014). [http://www.mlive.com/lansing-news/index.ssf/2014/03/michigan_unemployment_rate_dro.html Michigan unemployment rate plummets to 7.8 percent in January, lowest point since 2008] ''MLive.com.''</ref> During that same period Michigan saw its population base shrink.<ref>Witsil, Frank (January 9, 2014). [http://www.freep.com/article/20140109/BUSINESS06/301100055/michigan-migration-balanced-economy Based on moves, Michigan population loss tapers off, indicating improving economy] ''Detroit Free Press.''</ref> Speaker Bolger in 2011 worked with Republicans in the house to pass tax, education and pension reform measures, and employers have responded positively to the changes.<ref name=CapCon />  Since the reforms were passed in 2011 more than 250,000 jobs have returned to the state.<ref name=BLSnumbers /> During Bolger's time as Speaker from 2011 through 2013 Michigan has the fifth highest job growth in the nation.<ref name=CapCon>Gantert, Tom (January 3, 2014). [http://www.michigancapitolconfidential.com/19491 Michigan Among the Leaders in Job Growth] ''Michigan Capitol Confidential.''</ref><ref name=BLSnumbers />

===Right to Work===
In 2012 Michigan became the nation's 24th [[Right-to-work law|right-to-work]] state.<ref name=CNNRTW>Bennet, William (December 13, 2012). [http://edition.cnn.com/2012/12/12/opinion/bennett-michigan-unions/ A Victory For Right To Work Laws] ''CNN.''</ref> Prior to passage, Speaker Bolger was the sole legislative leader who supported right-to-work when other Michigan Republicans were lukewarm on the idea.<ref name=RTWMPRN>Clark, Zoe and Rick Pluta (February 21, 2014). [http://michiganradio.org/post/auto-no-fault-overhaul-gop-s-holy-grail Auto No-fault overhaul GOP's Holy Grail] ''Michigan Public Radio Network.''</ref><ref name=MLiveRTW>Luke, Peter (January 13, 2011). [http://www.mlive.com/politics/index.ssf/2011/01/new_house_speaker_jase_bolger.html New House Speaker Jase Bolger says 'right-to-work' status is 'on the table'] ''MLive.com.''</ref> The day Bolger was elected Speaker of the Michigan House of Representatives he stated that fellow Republicans should join him in reviewing the potential for right-to-work legislation.<ref name=MLiveRTW />

Under Speaker Bolger's leadership as Speaker, right-to-work legislation was introduced and passed by the House on December 6, 2012.<ref name=MCRTW>Mackinac Center [http://www.michigancapitolconfidential.com/media/images/2013/RTWtimelineWeb.jpg Virtual Timeline] ''Michigan Capitol Confidential.''</ref>  The legislation was eventually signed by Governor [[Rick Snyder]] on December 11, 2012.<ref name=MCRTW /> One year after the legislation passed more than 60,000 new jobs have been created in the state.<ref name=BLSnumbers>Bureau of Labor Statistics [http://data.bls.gov/timeseries/LASST260000000000005?data_tool=XGtable Data, tables and calculators by subject] ''Bureau of Labor Statistics.''</ref>

===Tax reform and venture capital growth===
Speaker Bolger worked with Senate Majority Leader Randy Richardville and Governor Snyder to pass tax reform in the state.<ref>Michigan Chamber of Commerce (February 17, 2011). [http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/michigan-chamber-of-commerce-applauds-governor-snyders-approach-to-tax-reform-and-balancing-of-state-budget-116421634.html Michigan Chamber of Commerce Applauds Governor Snyder's Approach to Tax Reform and Balancing of State Budget] ''PR Newswire.''</ref> The tax overhaul was the largest in 17 years, and included eliminating the Michigan Business Tax, reforming the personal income and pension tax systems.<ref>Luke, Peter (May 25, 2011). [http://www.mlive.com/politics/index.ssf/2011/05/gov_rick_snyder_signs_michigan.html Gov. Rick Snyder signs Michigan business/income tax overhaul into law] ''MLive.com''</ref> The changes in corporate tax structure have resulted in Michigan improving its corporate tax business environment from an all-time low ranking of 49th up to seventh-best in the country.<ref>Robyn, Mark (February 10, 2012). [http://taxfoundation.org/blog/michigan-implements-positive-corporate-tax-reform Michigan implements positive corporate tax reform] ''Tax Foundation.''</ref> Under the new tax changes, Michigan has become a top state for venture capital projects with 312 new projects in 2013.<ref name="Cover Story: Double Take">Arend, Mark (March 2014). [http://siteselection.com/issues/2014/mar/cover.cfm Cover Story: Double Take] ''Site Selection.''</ref>  The state ranks fifth in new project development, and 10th for projects per capita.<ref name="Cover Story: Double Take"/>

In addition to the reforms already in place, the House has legislation to improve the personal property tax system in Michigan.<ref name=PPTreform>Oosting, Jonathan (February 25, 2014). [http://www.mlive.com/lansing-news/index.ssf/2014/02/michigan_personal_property_tax_1.html Michigan personal property tax reform plan hailed as 'win-win' for businesses, local governments] ''MLive.com.''</ref> The personal property tax legislation, which is supported by the Lieutenant Governor [[Brian Calley]], would allow for 100 percent reimbursement to municipalities and an 80 percent reduction in business taxes based on the previous system.<ref name=PPTreform />

===Balancing the budget===
When Speaker Bolger assumed his new role the state was facing a $1.8 billion budget deficit, noting the budget deficit was a concern Bolger worked with Republicans to balance the budget.<ref name=MLive /> Prior to becoming Speaker, Michigan saw annual budget shortfalls of $1.5 billion on average, as well as repeated government shutdowns.<ref name=MLive /><ref name=MLiveBudget>Bridge Magazine (July 12, 2013). [http://www.mlive.com/opinion/index.ssf/2013/07/rep_jase_bolger_with_tough_dec.html Rep. Jase Bolger: With tough decisions, GOP lawmakers put Michigan on path for better future] ''MLive.com''</ref> In his first year as Speaker, Bolger, Senate Majority Leader [[Randy Richardville]] and Governor [[Rick Snyder]] worked to pass a budget which resulted in Michigan seeing a more than $450 million surplus.<ref name=NYTimes>Davey, Monica (February 8, 2012). [http://www.nytimes.com/2012/02/09/us/surplus-surprises-michigan-but-is-it-safe-to-spend-again.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0 Surplus Surprises Michigan, but Is It Safe to Spend Again?] ''New York Times.''</ref>

In each subsequent year the Michigan legislature has passed, and the governor has signed a balanced budget.<ref name="michigan.gov"/> In each of the past three years, Michigan has seen a surplus that has also helped replenish the state's Rainy Day Fund, which in 2011 had $2.2 million in reserves and now is projected to surpass $700 million in reserves for the 2014-15 fiscal year budget.<ref name=FreepRDF>Egan, Paul and Kathleen Gray (February 5, 2014). [http://www.freep.com/article/20140204/NEWS06/302040156/Gov-Snyder-s-budget-plan-calls-for-more-in-Rainy-Day-Fund Gov. Snyder's budget plan calls for 6.1% hike for universities, more in Rainy Day Fund] ''Detroit Free Press.''</ref><ref>State of Michigan [http://www.michigan.gov/midashboard/0,4624,7-256-59631_59883_60045---,00.html Michigan Rainy Day Fund] ''Michigan.gov.''</ref>

===Detroit revitalization===
Speaker Bolger has stated that he plans to work with legislators on both sides of the aisle to assist Detroit in its [[Planning and development in Detroit|revitalization]].<ref name=Detroit>Riley, Rochelle (November 3, 2013). [http://www.freep.com/article/20131103/COL10/311030064/Jase-Bolger-Michigan-Detroit Rochelle Riley: Speaker Bolger gets busy on Detroit's plight, but not all lawmakers are persuaded] ''Detroit Free Press.''</ref> In October 2013, the Speaker visited Detroit with state Representative [[Harvey Santana]], a Democrat from Michigan's 9th house district, and pledged to explore ways to fight crime, lower auto insurance rates and clean up the city.<ref name=Detroit /> After the visit Speaker Bolger met with the [[Michigan State Police]] to discuss alternatives to fighting crime, as well as discussing plans about alternative sentencing options with other legislators.<ref name=Detroit />

Also, since that visit the Speaker has worked with local Detroit representatives to garner support for scrap metal theft legislation and education reform.<ref>Livengood, Chad (March 19, 2014). [http://www.detroitnews.com/article/20140319/POLITICS02/303190087/Michigan-House-approves-scrap-metal-theft-reforms Michigan House approves scrap metal theft reforms] ''The Detroit News.''</ref><ref>Eggert, David (March 20, 2014). [http://www.sfgate.com/news/article/House-OKs-school-turnaround-district-legislation-5335708.php House OKs school turnaround district legislation] ''Associated Press.''</ref> Most recently, the Speaker proposed a change to Michigan's auto insurance laws, which would help reduce cost for Detroit's drivers; after promoting his proposal the Speaker met with Representatives [[John Olumba]] and Santana in an effort to create bi-partisan reform.<ref>Briscoe, Tony (March 21, 2014) [http://www.detroitnews.com/article/20140321/POLITICS02/303210130 Auto insurance reform sought] ''The Detroit News.''</ref>

==Political controversies==

===2012 Womens' Health Rights===
On June 13, 2012, Speaker Bolger allegedly refused to recognize fellow Michigan [[Lisa Brown (Michigan politician)|Rep. Lisa Brown]] for a full service day after she utilized the term "vagina" during a floor debate over a bill (HB 5711) to further regulate abortion in the state.<ref>{{cite news|last=Bergstrom|first=William|title=Michigan state Rep. Lisa Brown silenced for saying <U+2018>vagina<U+2019>|url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0612/77445.html|accessdate=8 January 2014|newspaper=Politico|date=14 June 2012}}</ref> Speaker Bolger denies this allegation, saying Rep. Brown was sanctioned by the Majority Floor Leader for violating the rules of the house, based on how she addressed the Speaker Pro Tem when she concluded her speech with "Mr. Speaker, I'm flattered that you're all so interested in my vagina, but no means no."<ref name=LisaBrown>Peralta, Eyder (June 14, 2012). [http://www.npr.org/blogs/thetwo-way/2012/06/14/155059849/michigan-state-rep-barred-from-speaking-after-vagina-comments Michigan State Rep Barred From Speaking After 'Vagina' Comments]. ''National Public Radio (NRP)''.</ref>

===Party switch controversy===
In 2012, Bolger worked with then-Democratic Michigan state Rep. [[Roy Schmidt (politician)|Roy Schmidt]] to switch parties at the filing deadline.<ref name=SchmidtParty>Reens, Nate (May 15, 2012). [http://www.mlive.com/news/grand-rapids/index.ssf/2012/05/rep_roy_schmidt_announces_part.html#incart_river_default Grand Rapids Rep. Roy Schmidt announces party switch, long-time Democrat will run as Republican] ''Grand Rapids Press''.</ref> Schmidt expressed dissatisfaction with what he called extreme party bosses in the Democratic party.<ref name=SchmidtParty /> Schmidt recruited a replacement for Democrats, 22-year old Matt Mojzak, who would not mount a campaign, leaving the Democrats without a serious candidate.<ref>Egan, Paul (August 28, 2012). [http://www.freep.com/article/20120828/NEWS06/120828021/House-speaker-Bolger-says-Rep-Schmidt-told-him-fake-candidate-s-residency-legit House speaker Bolger says Rep. Schmidt told him fake candidate's residency was legit] ''Detroit Free Press''.</ref> With no serious Democratic candidate, Schmidt effectively ensured his victory as a Republican.<ref name=MojzakHuff>Abbey-Lambertz, Kate (July 19, 2012). [http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/07/18/roy-schmidt-jase-bolger-michigan-gop-house-_n_1684026.html Roy Schmidt, Jase Bolger, Michigan State Rep And Speaker, Not Charged After Election Scandal] ''Huffington Post''.</ref> Schmidt offered to pay Mojzak $450 to file as the Democratic challenger.<ref name=MojzakHuff /> Schmidt upped the amount to $1,000 when Mojzak announced he was going to withdraw his candidacy.<ref name=MojzakHuff />

Bolger was involved in the scandal, as demonstrated by text messages that he exchanged with Schmidt.<ref name=ReensTexts>Reens, Nate (July 18, 2012). [http://www.mlive.com/news/grand-rapids/index.ssf/2012/07/read_text_message_exchange_bet.html Read text messages between House Speaker Bolger, Rep. Schmidt plotting party switch, fake candidate] ''Grand Rapids Press''.</ref> Bolger helped Schmidt switch parties, but Bolger stated, and no evidence has shown Bolger knew that Schmidt offered money to Mojzak to run.<ref name=ReensTexts /><ref name=DFP>Egan, Paul (July 18, 2012). [http://www.freep.com/article/20120718/NEWS05/207180438/State-House-speaker-representative-blamed-in-election-candidate-scam?odyssey=tab State House speaker, representative blamed in election candidate scam]. ''Detroit Free Press''. Retrieved July 20, 2012.</ref> Several independent investigations and a grand jury review showed that Bolger did not break any rules at any time.<ref>Oosting, Jonathan (August 09, 2013). [http://www.mlive.com/politics/index.ssf/2013/08/jase_bolger_roy_schdmit_cleare.htm Jase Bolger, Roy Schmidt cleared in grand jury investigation of party-switch schemel] ''MLive.com''.</ref> Ingham County Circuit Judge Rosemarie Aquilina wrote that an exhaustive and diligent probe uncovered no crime or wrongdoing, and that an indictment was not warranted.<ref name=CBSDetroit>Eggert, Dave (August 9, 2013). [http://detroit.cbslocal.com/2013/08/09/no-indictment-after-michigan-party-switch-probe/ No Indictment after Michigan Party Switch Probe]. ''CBS Detroit.''</ref> Additionally, Bolger authored an [[op-ed]] in the [[Detroit Free Press]] where he offered voters his apology and noted he made a mistake.<ref name=apology>Bolger, Jase (July 20, 2012). [http://www.freep.com/article/20120720/OPINION05/120720055/Speaker-Bolger-I-apologizes-to-voters- Michigan House Speaker Bolger: 'I apologize to voters']. ''Detroit Free Press''.</ref>

